{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_eustachy_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532579/1920110401/0081.xml":{"full_text":"Harc?ng ^Wiiis\nGty by 440,041\nIn Record Run\nFinal Returns, Giving PIu-!\nrality for Smith in All\nBoronghs as 419,611, As\ntounds Loral Politicians\n__\nDebs and Cox Vote Close\nDemocrats Only Able to\nSave the Bench Ticket in\nSecond Judicial District\nCorrected return? yesterday only em\nj)b*?***d the Republican ?weep in New\nYork City for Harding: and Coolidge.\nThey carried th? city with a plurality\nof 440,041 over Cox and Roosevelt.\nTh? Harding-Coolidge vote in all the\nboroughs except Richmond was more\nthan twice that of the Democratic na?\ntional candidates. Never before has\nthe city given so large a plurality to\nany Presidential candidate. President\nWilson carried the city !n 1916 by\n40,000.\nThe final showing in the city of Gov?\nernor Smith was a marvel to the local j\npoliticians of both parties. Complete\nreturns fixed the Governor's plurality\nover Judge Miller at. 419.611. The Gov-j\nirr.nr's great i un ahead of his state\nticket, together with a comparatively'\nr.?c'. gible vote for Governor Cox. mane\nAl even stronger in defeat with the\nloca! organisation. A hoomlet was born\nfor h's candidacy for Mayor next year.\nBig Brooklyn Vote for Smith\nTh? Smith vote in Brooklyn, where I\nt'nera is always an element of doubt\nas to what the mass of voters will do.\nexceeded the rosiest prediction of the\nXings County Democratic leaders. The\nGovernor's plurality in that horough\nwas 88,974. lie received 242,392 votes,\nas compared with 202.227 in 1918. j\nSenator James W, Wadsworth carried\nN'e.w York City safely. He ran behind\nhis partv in 'he city, due probably to\nthe opposition of the women's vote,\nbat, on a basis of incomplete returns.\nhe hsd an indiea'ed plurality of 32,000.\nIn Brooklyn he received 214,502 votes,\nas apa nst 152,110 for Lieutenant Gov?\nernor Harrj C. Walker, his Democratic\nopponent or -'rc United States Sen\natorship.\nThe final city figures showed 'hat\nEugene Debs, Socialist candidate for\nPresident, ran close 10 Governor Cox in\nthe Bronx Debls poil? 32,782 in 'hat.\nborough and Cox, 45,747. The Debs vote\nin the ent re city was 131.856, as com?\npared ?nth 31,788 for Benson, the\nSocialist candidate for President in\n1916.\nSenator Harding carried every As?\nsembly district in the city, with the\nexception of the ?1st Assembly dis?\ntrict in Manhattan, which is Governor\nSmith's home district.. Cox's plural?\nity in th s district was 41o. while Gov?\nernor Smith received almost: 10,000\nvotes out of a total of about 13,000\nIn the 12th Assembly District. Man?\nhattan, n which Charles F. Murphy\nresidas, Cbx ran clo e to Harding hv\n10,763 to 11,430. Th? district polls\nabout 22,000 votes. Governor Smith\nran waj ahead of Cox in the Murphy\ndistrict, receiving 17.141 votes to 4,477:\nfor the Ohio Governor. In 1916 Wilson\nreeebved 3,721 votes and Hughes 1,758 in j\nthis district\nThir Fle lican candidates below the\nGovernor on the st?ate ticket ran eon\nsiderably ahead of Judge Miller in the\ncity. John T. Lyons. Republican candi?\nda'? for Secretary of State, made an\nexceptionally good showing in the\ngrea\"-r city He apparently carried all\nthe boroughs over 'ri opponent. Har?\nre' May Mills. In Manhattan, with\nonly seventy-seven election districts\nmissile o it of a total of 998. his vote\nwas 205,624 to 145,462 for Miss Mills.\nThe complete returns from Brooklyn\ngave. Ltyons 235,263; Mills. 148,727.\nWith tw?o election districts missing out\nof Beventy-six in Richmond, Lyons got\n12,644 to 11,638 for Mills.\nWVndell's Lead Increased\nComplete returns from Brooklyn gave\nJames A. Wendell, Republican candi?\ndate for State Comptroller, 205,3*)9,\nand Charlee \\V. Berry, Democratic\ncandidate, 171,871, In Queens the vote\nwa- Wendell, 11,919; Berry, 8,953. State\nSenator H M. Marshal!, Republican\ncandidate for S'ate Treasurer, carried\nthe city by a vote of about 515,000 to\n448,000 for John F. Healy, Democrat.\nTUr, only conspicuous thine the !.>ra!\nDemocratic organization saved from\nthe wreck, apparently, was the judi?\nciary ticket in 'he 2d Judicial District\n(Manhattan ami the Bronx?, where the\nreturn.- last right, though\" still incom?\nplete, indicated 'he election of the\nfou*- Den? Mcrat.ic j'istice* for the\nSupreme onr* District Attorney\nRwann ran several thousand votes be?\nhind his running mate? on the Demo?\ncratic cket and James O'Malley, the\nw? not more O?an 2.000 votes behind\nSwann. Thr-re were 399 election dis-\ntricts missing out of a total of 993.\nwhich left a chance of some, of the Re- i\npublicans nosing in at the finish. The\nfive canditiates for the Supreme Court\nindorsed for reelection by both parties\nwere sure of election.\nThe Republicans elected all five, can?\ndidates for the Supreme Court in the\n2d Judicial District (Brooklyn. Queens\nand Richmond). With only forty-eight\nelection districts missing out of'a total\nof 977, Justice Jaycox, who was last on j\nthe Republican ticket with the least\nnumber of votes, was nevertheless 35.- I\n000 votes ahead of Justice Scudder,\nwho headed the Democratic list with I\nthe largest number of votes. The sue\ncessfu] Republican justices are Norman\nS. Pike, Joseph Aspinall, John Mac\nCrate. Walter H. Jaycox and Se.lah B.\nStrong. Jacob S. Strata, Municipal\nCourt justice, who ran m the 2d Bis\ntrict without party indorsement, polled\na surpnsing'y larg?? vote, indicated at\nalmost 100,000 when the returns are\nall in.\nThe Democrats were able to return\nsome of their members to Congress\nfrom the city, as well as state Senators\nand Assemblymen in tne strong Demo?\ncratic districts, but the Republicans\nmade gains in all three cases. Daniel\nJ. Riordan, Tammany candidate in the\n11th Congressional District, was ap?\nparently re?lected, as were Peter J.\nDooling in the 15th and John F. Carew\nin the 18th District. W. Bourke Cock\nran appeared to have been electe?! in\nthe 16th District. In Kings, Thomas\nH. (Julien. Democrat, apparently was j\nelee%ed in the 4th District. Andrew X.\nPetersen, Republican, seemed to have\ndefeated David J. O'Connell in the 9th\nDistrict, which is partly in Kings and\nQueens. In Queens, the present Rep?\nresentative, Frederick C. Hicks, of Port\nWashington, was reflected.\nOgden Milla Elected\nThe Republicans elected Ogden L.\nMills, in the 17th District, and Wai?\nter M. Chandler, in the 19th, to Con?\ngress, and made other gains through?\nout the city.\nQueens County Republicans yester?\nday celebrated the biggest victory in\nthe history of the party in that\nborough since consolidation of the\ngreater city. It has been twenty-two\nyears since a Republican Sheriff was\nelected in that county, and eighteen\nyears since a Republican was elected\n,District Attorney. The election of\nRepublicans to these two offices was a\nhard blow to the regular Democratic\n'organization. headed by Borough\nPresident Maurice E. Connolly. John\n1 Wagner, Deputy Commissioner of\nJurors, was elected Sheriff over\nBorotigh Secretary Joseph Flannagan.\nConsiderable patronage, is connected\nwith the Sheriff's office. Danna Wal?\nlace was elected District Attorney\nover Lawrence T. Gresser, son of th?\n(former Queens Borough President, and\n?the present District Attorney, Denis\nO'Leary, who ran independently.\nThe Republicans repeated their vic?\ntory r>f last year in Queens, electing\nfooir out of six Assemblymen and one\nof the two slat? Senators,\nAlmost completed returns last night\nshtowed the election of Gustave Hart\nman, Republican candidate ir>r the\nCfitv Court in Manhattan. John G.\nMcr?igue, Democrat, was elected to the\nMunicipal Court. 4th District. Man?\nhattan. In the Municipal Court, 7th\nDistrict, Brooklyn, Harrison C. Glore,\nRepublican, was elected.\n.Robert L. Moran, former Democratic\nPresident of the Board of Aldermen,\nwars reelerted County Clerk in the\nBronx. C. Livingston Bostwick was\nreflected County Clerk in Richmond.\nOno Democrat Wins Office\nDutches*? County Almost Solid\nFor Republican Candidates\nSpecial Dispatch to The Tribune\nPOUGHKEEPSIE, N. Y., Nov. 3.\nDutches? County elected but a single\n.Democrat, John M. Mulvey, Pough\n.?.eepsie Alderman. All 'he other rnTlces\nof the county, both ?rreat and small,\njare to h? filled by Republicans.\nThe plurality for Harding and\nC'oohdge in Dutches? is 11,139. Cox\nand Rooseve!?- received 10,210 and\nHarding and Coolidge 21,340 votes.\nMiller received 18,404 votes and\nSmith 12.34*. Wadsworth received is..\n944 and Walker 8,947 votes. Wads\nworth carried the county by *.P00. Fish\nreceived 1.00\" plurality in eight dis?\ntricts. It is estimated trat tne wom?\nen's opposition to Wadsworth cost him\n1,000 votes in Dutchess County alone.\nThe county gave 2,000 to Mrs. Ella\nBoole. Poughkeepsie gave Wadsworth\na plurality of 2,RO0.\nFrank L. Gardiner, Republican, won\nover Yende^ater in this district, his\nmajority being C.SIO in Poughkeepsie\nand 441 in the outlying towns, making\n3.061 for the ?ntire district.\nJ. Griswold Webb, Republican, won\nin the 1st DistricL with 5.000 majority\nover A. F. Abbot* Democrat, carrying\nevery election district except the 4th\nDistrict of Fallkill, where he tied his\nopponent, 25 to 25.\nDemocratic Chains Smashed\nBy Irish, Says J. D. Moore\nJohn D. Moore, first national secre?\ntary of the Friends of Irish Freedom\nand an active leaguer, in commenting\nyesterday on 'he defeat of Cox and\nRooseve?t, said:\n\"The Irish nave broken their Demo?\ncratic chains *nd smashed the Demo?\ncratic party, They have demonstrated\nthat Irish 'independence is a domestic\nquestion right here in the United\nStales.\"\nSUPER-SECURITY\nFOR ANY AMOUNT\nFirst Mortgages are rightly out at the\nfoundation of a wise, diversified invest?\nment. Our offerings have the certifica?\ntion of a strong financial institution\nabsolutely guaranteeing their payment.\nYour choice of many, such as\nAmount\nof_I,oan\n_ $2.000\"\n$3,000\n$5,500\n$10.000\nRental\nOwner\nOwner\n~$f.38? _\n$2,208\nValue of\nSecurity\n$7^500\n$10,000\n$^obo_~\n$17,500\nGuaranteed First Mortgage Certificates from $100 up.\nBand for Booklet 3 B\nNEW YORK\nTITLE MORTGAGE\nCOMPANY\n133 Broadway\nNew York\n375 Fol ton St.,\nJamaica\n203 Montagne St.\nBrooklyn\nBridge Piara,\nL. I. City\njECUREesTHE.BEPRO?Ko^HgyryORjK\nPredict Record\nBusiness Era\nUnder Harding\nBankers and Leaders in\nCommerce See Propress\nand Prosperity in Land?\nslide for Republicans\ni\n8-Year Term, Says Gary\nStrong Cabinet, Declares\nSteel Head, Will Insure\nPeriod of Achievements\nLeaders in the world of finance and\nbusiness expressed elation yesterday\nover the landslide that swept the Re?\npublican national ticket to victory af-l\nter eight years under a Democratic\nAdministration. There was a genera!\nfeeling that confidence had been re?\nstored and that Senator Harding, pro?\nviding he surrounds himself with able\nadvisers, will he fully etjual to the\nemergency confronting him.\nOn the Stock Exchange trading was\nstill affected by considerations outside\nof the realm of politics, but brokers\nagreed that after the present period\nof readjustment has passed the ?e\nturity markets will reflect the feeling\nof greater confidence in the business\noutlook. While the industrial list\nhesitated, railroad shares moved for?\nward under the leadership of Southern\nPacific and Reading.\nElbert H. Gary, chairman of the\nUnited States Steel Corporation, re?\nflecting the opinion of many other\nleaders in the iron and steel industry,\npredicted an eight-year term for Presi?\ndent-elect Harding if he picks able\nmen as his advisers. In the opinion\nof Judge Gary, the country will ex?\nperience recor?! prosperity and prog?\nress should the Republican party live\nup to its opportunities and responsi?\nbilities.\nPredicts larger Prosperity\n\"I am, of course, very much pleased\nby the result of the election,\" said\nJudge Gary. \"The Republican party\nhas great opportunities anil equally\ngreat responsibilities, If it measures\nup to the situation, we will experience\nin the future more rapid progress ami\nlarger prosperity than ever before.\nThere is much to do and every one\nshould do his full share in bringing\nabout normal conditions.\n\"With a strong Cabinet and appro?\npriate appointments, the neu- Adminis?\ntration is certain of an eight years'\ntprm and a record of achievement\nwhich will have a derided influence on\nthe welfare of the people ?n th;- coun?\ntry and other countries as well. Yes?\nterday was a great day for civilization.\nPresident Harding and Vice-President\nCoolidge will have the cordial support\nof the financial, commercial and indus?\ntrial interests of this country and. in\nturn, will render every proper and\npracticable aid toward the attainment\nof economy, efficiency n:id happiness\nof .-iii who are deserving.\n\"The election demonstrates very\nforcibly one thing: the women are fully\ncapable of exercising the right of fran?\nchise. The country is safer because of\ntheir right and willingness to vote.\"\nGfwd Effect on Business.\nViews cf leading hankers on Senator\nHarding's election* follow\nE. V, R. Thayer, president of the\nChase National Bank The result ''f\nthe election will have a good effect on\nbusiness. H will have a stabilizing\ntendency. People may now look for?\nward with some assurance of steady\nconditions and may know pretty well\nwhat to expect for n considerable time\nto come. Irrespective of p'->':'i--.c?>i\nopinion, people are triad to have the\nfuture clearly mapped out.\nMortimer Schiff, of Kuhn. Loeb f:\nCo,?I believe the election of Warren\nG. Harding will 'nave a stimulating\neffect on all business. The Republican\nparty has always been a cor.-:ervativo\norganization.\nBarton Hepburn, chairman of the ad?\nvisory board of the Chase National\nBank I am greatly pleased with the\nre ult. Harding's majority was much\nlarger than expected.\nRepublicans Continue\nTo Gain in New Jersey\n-(j\nRevised Returns Give Plurality\nof 279,995 to Har.ling; One'\nWet Democrat Elected\nTRENTON, N. J., Nov. 3 ?By The As?\nsociated Press). The Republican land?\nslide in New Jersey continued to mount\nto new hifrh record proportions on be?\nlated returns received to-night.\nRevised returns on all but 353 of the\n2,046 districts in the state gave Senator\nHarding a plurality of 1279,905 over Cox,\nor more than three times Hughe.?'*\nplurality in 191fi. The highest previ?\nous plurality was recorded in 1S96,\nwhen McKinley led Bryan by 87,f>9'2.\nThe returns tabulated alreadv Rive:\nHarding, 480,591; (ox. 200,546.\nRepublicans also gained four seat.?\nin Congress, giving ?hem eleven Rep?\nresentatives to one for the Democrats.\nThey also added thirteen to their ma?\njority in the State Assembly and main?\ntained their majority of nine in the\n?ta*e Senate. Charles F. X. O'Brien,\n'cunning on a wet platform, was the\nonly Democratic Congressman to he\nelected. He comes from Hudson Coun?\nty, -always a Democratic stronghold.\nHarry Runyon, of Warren County, was\nthe only Democrat elected to the State\nAssembly.\nm? i\nCox Acknowledges\nDefeat as Verdict\nOf the Majority\nGovernor Tenders Congratu?\nlations to Harding in\n\"Spirit of America\" and\nPromises Loyal Support\nSpfrial Dispatch m T>,r Tribune\nDAYTON, Ohio, Nov. 3.- Governor\nCox's only comment upon his defeat\nwas contained in a telegram to Senatoi\nHarding, offering congratulations, anri\nin an editorial in very much the samp\nvein as his telegram to President-elect\nHarding, which appeared in Cox's news.\npaper to-night.\n\"In the spirit of America I accept tb<\ndecision of the majority, tender a.? th?\ndefoHtod candidate my congratulations\nand pledge as a citizen my support ti?\nthe Executive authority in whatevei\nemergencv might arise.\"\nThe editorial, entitled \"The Elecfioi\nIs Over,\" was as follows.\n\"The election is over and the citizen;\nof the United States arc glad that it is\nfeeling r?ms high during a nationa\ncampaign, hut the moment that the de\ncisi?n of the electorate is announce?\nth? thought in the public mind is tha\nof pleasure that the event has passed\nThe spirit of America is that the voie\n??f the majority must rule in the na\ntion'.? affairs. From this traditiona\nstandpoint there must he no departur\nnow. Figures associated with the re\nsuits will he studied and conclusion\nreached in the ?nurse of time, Th-r\nwill soon be a return to our customar;\npursuits as a people. The period o\ncongratula ?ions over a victory wil\nmerge presently with the prompt obedi\nencc of our citizenship to the mandat\nof the men and women who this yea\nformed the majority.-\"\nCox rem a i ?led in the seclusion o\nTrailsend this morning, occupying him\nself with personal business. He wa\nnoticeably disappointed as iie scanne\nlater advice? telling of the extent o\nthe Republican victory and as h\nwatched the returns from Tenness?!?\nbut he was not depressed ,and when h\nleft Trailsend to motor to his fan\nnear Jacksonville he seemed in on]\nnary, if sober, spirits.\nHarding PoIlTl 7,090\nN otes in New Or!p;ni\nCarries Ten Known Countr\nParishes and I?* Easv ?dor\nin Othrr Districts\nNEW ORLEANS. Nov. 3.?.Senate\nHarding polled 'It* unprecedented tot\nof 17,090 votes in the city of N'ew O\nleans, with five of the 157- precinc\nmissing.\nHe carried ?en known country pa\n?shes, apparently was an easy victor\nthe 3d Congressional District anil e.gl\ncity precincts, mostly in the uptow\nresidence section, cave him maioritie\nA\nM\nUNDERWEAR'\nOst?b\\tsb*?\nTlrAOE mark\n\n?A\nPROTFCTION Ma'nst chiilinc of tne\nrunner of colds, pneuwonia und rheumatism.\nEVERY ?ARMENT^r^re\nand t'-iaraateed not to shrink.\n$2.50\nto $7.00\nt>r Garment\nRegular SU?*\nFine Cray Winter VVXf ht.\nfo-ir r.jilnira.\nFine Gray Suprr Weijiut.\nthree qualities.\nFine Worsttrd Merino,\nMedium weicht.\nFor Sale by Leae?og Dealer*\nIGSOnr BE'FS) CrMP?iTJ\n^KBnfiaaHVa UK'sthiaut?rrs\nWkir>r, fibrrr tfaswUsicf?ss?rrp!e*<ra.tii!rnf r..\nYour?? for- ?fi?> Jk&imr E&t??t\".. T..\nTM? 0U*^TONBUPY KNITTING CCJ\"\nCl?stoniu?v. Conn\nQuality vs. Quantity\nRead the experience of a School advertising in the\nInstruction Help Wanted Column' of The Tribune:\nAMERICAN COMMERCE ASSOCIATION\nEastern Office,\nS:4 Tribune Bldg.\nNew York\nOctober 27, 1920.\nNew ork Tribune, 154 Nassau Street, New York Cm-,\nGentlemen\nDuring the pa? year -we have been using The New York Tribune\nas a medium in reaching the ela*s of young men who are desirous o?\nbettering themselves through home stud? instruction.\nFrom the very beginning we have been verv well pleased with the\nresults we have obtained from copv placed in New York Tribune\nWhile the number of replie? ha? been les? than from other\nmedium* which we have uted, the quality of replie? ha? been\nsuperior.\nt To say the least, we are more than satisfied with the results ob?\ntained from The Tribune.\nVery trulj- vours,\nAMERICAN' COMMERCE ASSOCIATION.\nA. W. Rhamstine, District Manager.\nPresident ?Won't\nDiscuss Defeat\nOf His Policies\nMr. Wilson Follows Usual\nRoutine and Refuses to\nComment on the Result of\n*fc Solemn Referendum\nCabinet Also Reticent\nColby and Seeretary Wil?\nson Only Officials Who\nWill Discuss Election\nFrom The Tribune's Washington Burea*\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 3. President\nWilson remained silent to-day on the\neiushing defeat administered to the\nDemocratic party, an 1 the repudiation\ncf the Wilson League of Nations by\nAmerican vote:-= yesterday.\nThe Executive made no statement\neither to his personal physician, Dr.\nCary T. Grayson, or his private sec?\nretary, Joseph P, Tumulty, that would\nindicate the extent to which his emo?\ntions were stirred by the Republican\nlandslide in yesterday's \"solemn ref?\nerendum.\"\nWhite House officials were unable to\nsay whether the President contem?\nplated sending a message of congratu?\nlation t?? Senator Harding, or of re?\ngret to Governor Cox, the defeated\ncandidate. They did not expect him\nto have any comment to make on the\nelection at this time.\nThis silence likewise was reflected\nto a ?arpe decree in the President's\nCabinet. Secretary Baker flatly re\nfu.-ed to comment, on the result. Sec?\nretary of the Interior Payne spent the\nafternoon at the golf course and made\nno statement on the election. Post?\nmaster General Burleson dismissed all\ninquirers with the blunt statement:\nI have nothing to say. The result\nspeaks for itself.\" Secretary cf the\nTreasury Houston likewise was with?\nout comment, and Secretary of Agri?\nculture Meredith did not. advance any\nstatement of his views. Secretaries\nDaniels an?! Alexander and Attorney\nGeneral Palmer were absent from\nWashington.\nThe only Cabinet members w?io gave\ni nj' hint of their regret were Sec?\nretary of State Hainbridge Colby, who,\nin expressing regret, advanced the hope\nthat the Leur'!?' of Nations might, :n\nsome way, he joined by this govern?\nment, and Secretary of Labor Wilson,\nwho scut n m 's?h^. of condolence to\nvernor Cox.\nSecretary Colby said: \"It. would be\nidle for me to say that I am not de?\npressed and disappointed by the re\n-r.lt, but 'hope springs eternal in the\nhuman breast,' and I cannot but feel\nthat in some way and by some avenue\nM?! at the moment disclosed, th\" coun?\ntry will act up to the highest concep?\ntion of its role und its duty.\"\nSecretary Wilson in his message to\n(?ove?nor Cox said\n\"Von have fought a \"'?a', tight. You\nhave knpt the faith. ''1 ruth crushed te\nearth will rise again. The eternal\nyears of t',oi\\ are hers.' It is beftej- to\nlose in a cause that is right than to\nwin in a cause that is wrong.\"\nSecretary Tumulty would not add\nanything to his statement of last night,\nin which he said that he rejoiced to be\nwith the President \"in this hour of\nDemocratic defeat.\"\nDr. Grayson announced that the elec?\ntion result hail no a